18. @FunctionalInterface ANNOTATION
============================================================

Example:

```java
@FunctionalInterface
interface Calculator {

    int calculate(int a, int b);

}
```


`@FunctionalInterface` annotation compiler ko indicate karta hai ki interface ko Functional Interface ke roop me maintain karna hai.


Agar second abstract method add karenge:

```java
@FunctionalInterface
interface Calculator {

    int add(int a, int b);

    int subtract(int a, int b);

}
```


Compile-time error aayega.


IMPORTANT:

`@FunctionalInterface` annotation mandatory nahi hai.


Ye bhi Functional Interface hai:

```java
interface Calculator {

    int calculate(int a, int b);

}
```


Lekin annotation use karna good practice hai.


============================================================
19. FUNCTIONAL INTERFACE ME DEFAULT METHOD
============================================================

Functional Interface me exactly one abstract method hona chahiye.

Lekin multiple default methods ho sakte hain.


Example:

```java
@FunctionalInterface
interface Demo {

    void show();


    default void print() {

        System.out.println("Print");

    }

}
```


Ye valid Functional Interface hai.


Kyunki abstract method sirf:

```java
void show();
```

hai.


============================================================
20. FUNCTIONAL INTERFACE ME STATIC METHOD
============================================================

Static methods bhi allowed hain.


Example:

```java
@FunctionalInterface
interface Demo {

    void show();


    static void test() {

        System.out.println("Test");

    }

}
```


Ye valid hai.


Functional Interface restriction:

```text
Exactly One Abstract Method
```


Not:

```text
Exactly One Total Method
```


